                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-22T13:35:59.047-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Searching for ways to combat COVID-19"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:29:58.051-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Every day for months, Teresa Ng has been receiving pop-up notifications of new research reports related to COVID-19 on her computer.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>In a way, this is good. She is getting to know her target better every day.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Ng is a 20-year veteran of AbbVie, where she is a principal research scientist and has helped discover and develop antiviral therapies for both hepatitis C virus (HCV) and HIV. Today, she’s bringing that experience to bear during an unprecedented global pandemic. That’s because Ng, like so many other scientists around the world, is trying to answer the call of a lifetime. She’s part of the AbbVie research team that’s looking for a way to combat COVID-19.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <image
                                cq:styleIds="[1402843082812,1402843082822,1402843082832]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:38:54.713-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:26:18.101-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Teresa Ng, principal research scientist, virology drug discovery, leads a team of scientists at AbbVie’s labs in Lake County, Illinois, U.S."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="How AbbVie is bringing "
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/how-abbvie-is-bringing-antiviral-expertise-to-the-covid-19-battle/TeresaNg_121.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:38:54.811-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:38:54.811-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:40:43.235-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:40:57.729-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>“We’ve built a deep expertise on antiviral therapies, particularly through our work with HCV and HIV, and now we have the opportunity to apply what we’ve learned to one of the most urgent scientific challenges of our lifetime,” Ng said.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>It’s a daunting mission, but here’s some good news: As the world faces an unparalleled healthcare crisis in the battle against the COVID-19 pandemic, clinicians, researchers, governments and non-governmental organizations are pooling their resources, combining expertise and sharing preliminary data to help accelerate a race for effective treatments.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>While developing an effective vaccine is critical, it is also important to have other options for treatment. People need options for treatment if they become infected with COVID-19. Also, there are a number of people who might not react well to a vaccine, due to their age or a previously weakened immune system.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
                            <image_797811470
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:42:28.667-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:52.010-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Principal research scientist Xiaofeng Xin discusses his work with senior scientist colleague Danyal Butt in the lab at AbbVie’s Worcester, Massachusetts, U.S. site."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="Principal research scientist Xiaofeng Xin"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/how-abbvie-is-bringing-antiviral-expertise-to-the-covid-19-battle/ABBVIE_07212020_028.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_207116806
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:43:25.751-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:43:25.751-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:43:46.889-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:44:55.105-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>That’s where antivirals like the one AbbVie is working on come in.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Answers for the disease have still not been found, but a number of promising leads are under investigation. Building on its expertise in antibody drug discovery and virology, AbbVie is collaborating with leading global research institutes to investigate and unlock the potential of fully humanized monoclonal antibodies that may help fight COVID-19.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>At the first sign of the pandemic, AbbVie quickly began evaluating possible ways to address the challenge. AbbVie connected with Harbour BioMed, a company that had previously partnered with AbbVie and had recently tested antibodies that they had developed for SARS-CoV (the original SARS virus) for potency against SARS-CoV-2 (the novel virus that causes COVID-19). They found one antibody that could work against both viruses, and published the results in&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-020-16256-y&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; title=&quot;Nature Communications.&quot;>Nature Communications&lt;/a>.&lt;sup>1&lt;/sup>&amp;nbsp;Soon after, Harbour BioMed and two academic institutions, Utrecht University and Erasmus Medical Center, teamed up with AbbVie to develop this monoclonal antibody as a therapy to prevent and treat COVID-19.&lt;sup>2&lt;/sup>&amp;nbsp;Knowing that there wasn’t a moment to spare, the four entities hit the ground running on their work together the moment they could.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_207116806>
                            <image_88696733
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:45:09.250-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:34:27.215-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Senior scientist Danyal Butt take a moment to pose in AbbVie’s labs in Worcester, Massachusetts, U.S."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="Senior scientist Danyal Butt"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="true"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/how-abbvie-is-bringing-antiviral-expertise-to-the-covid-19-battle/ABBVIE_07212020_070.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_1706747642
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:46:18.045-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:46:18.045-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-29T16:33:57.789-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:46:36.241-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-09T22:46:57.072-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>“The world needs an answer for this pandemic ASAP and, instead of starting from scratch, we are collaborating with external experts to quickly develop a treatment,” Ng said.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>Antibody therapies have received attention for their potential to block SARS-CoV-2 before it can infect a person’s cells. SARS-CoV-2 has a protein on its surface that is involved in recognizing and enabling its entry to the host cells. After the viral entry, the virus injects its genetic material into the host cell, where it hijacks the host’s cellular machinery to make more copies of the virus. One possible way to fight the virus is to discover an antibody that blocks this viral entry protein from interacting with host cells.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_1706747642>
                            <video
                                cq:styleIds="[0]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-09T22:47:09.900-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T06:30:24.980-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="KANCHRX3"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/video/v2/video"
                                autoPlay="true"
                                brightcoveAutoPlay="false"
                                btnText="Watch 0:25"
